**902nd Day of Russian Special Military Operation in Ukraine**
The Russian Armed Forces continue to conduct a special military operation in Ukraine, announced by Russian President Vladimir Putin on February 24, 2022. According to Putin, the main objectives of the operation are 'demilitarization and denazification' of the neighboring country. After over a year of confrontations, the Russian Army, along with the forces of the Donetsk and Lugansk republics, has completely liberated the Lugansk People's Republic and part of the Donetsk republic, as well as the Kherson region, areas of Zaporozhie near the Azov Sea, and part of the Karkov region. In October 2022, following referendums in the regions, the Donetsk and Lugansk people's republics and the Kherson and Zaporozhie regions officially joined the Russian Federation. On May 20, 2023, the Russian Ministry of Defense confirmed that Russian forces had taken control of the city of Artyomovsk, or Bakhmut, in Ukrainian nomenclature, an important transportation center for supplying Ukrainian troops in Donbass. In June 2023, Ukraine attempted to launch a large counteroffensive in the combat zone, but it failed for the Ukrainian Armed Forces - a fact recognized by military experts and even by Western media. In early May 2024, the Russian Army began advancing towards Karkov, with the Sever (North) troop group taking control of several localities in the area. On May 17, Putin stated that Moscow has no intention of taking Karkov, but rather creating a 'buffer zone' to protect the population of Russian border regions that are almost daily attacked by Ukrainian Armed Forces. 'We are not going to take Karkov,' Putin said. 'We are creating a buffer zone to protect the population of our border regions that are almost daily attacked by the Ukrainian Armed Forces.' 
