**Russia's Summer Offensive Failure**
Russia is unlikely to launch a new, coordinated offensive along the hundreds of miles of front lines in eastern Ukraine this summer, according to Kyiv authorities and Western analysis. Andriy Yusov, a spokesperson for Ukraine's GUR military intelligence agency, said, 'A repeat of a broad offensive along the entire front line, like in February 2022, is out of the question for now.' Russia has slowly gained territory in eastern Ukraine, claiming the Donetsk city of Avdiivka in February 2024, but analysts and officials say Moscow is waging an attritional war, hoping to grind down opposition fighters and Kyiv's reserves of equipment. Ukraine receives significant aid from its Western backers, including military vehicles, but there are pressing questions over the future of military aid deliveries should former President Donald Trump clinch victory in the U.S. elections later this year. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky confirmed that F-16 fighter jets, donated by at least one of Kyiv's supporter countries, were already operational. A large-scale offensive from Russia could be more likely next year, suggested Nick Reynolds, a research fellow in land warfare at the London-based Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) think tank.
